title: International Festival of Inclusive Arts Festival Finale (with photos)
content_text:
p>
The following is issued on behalf of the International Festival of Inclusive 
Arts: The Festival Finale of the International Festival of Inclusive Arts features 
outstanding artists with and without disabilities from Mainland China, Russia 
and Hong Kong, bringing both adults and children a night of fun and beauty.  The Festival Finale will be held on December 10 at 7.30pm at the Auditorium of 
Kwai Tsing Theatre. Local "Dancing Heart Troupe" of St James' Settlement 
Rehabilitation Services and DancingAndy Creative Workshop will jointly stage a

Rehabilitation Services and DancingAndy Creative Workshop will jointly stage a 
new modern dance that presents the concept of social inclusion in "Smiling 
Heart". Wong Wing-kam, Chosen Power, together with puppeteers with different 
abilities will stage the innovative performance with shadows interpreting 
paintings based on the album of famous painter Liu Tung-mui in "Trajectories". In "Fun for All", internationally renowned Russian deaf theatre group, Toys 
Theatre will mix deaf theatre, dance, clown performance and drama to tell

Theatre will mix deaf theatre, dance, clown performance and drama to tell 
stories with music and body movements. The audience will not only sit back and 
enjoy the performance but also become a part of it. The fun certainly extends 
beyond the stage! World Disabled People's Achievement Fair award holder China Disabled People's 
Performing Art Troupe will perform the "Variety Show of Beauty", bringing the 
Festival Finale to a close and giving viewers an unforgettable experience of 
inclusive arts performances. Organised by the Health, Welfare and Food Bureau and the Arts with the Disabled

Association Hong Kong, the International Festival of Inclusive Arts will be held 
from December 2 to 10. Through diverse programmes like performances, 
exhibitions, a symposium, workshops and a carnival, the festival aims at 
providing an opportunity for participation in arts by people with and without 
disabilities, and promoting an inclusive society. Tickets at $80 per person are available at all URBTIX outlets. Discount tickets 
at $40 per person are available to senior citizens, people with disabilities and 
one minder each, full-time students and Comprehensive Social Security Assistance

one minder each, full-time students and Comprehensive Social Security Assistance recipients. Wheelchair seats are provided. For programme enquiries, call the Arts with the Disabled Association Hong Kong at 2855 9548; for ticketing enquiries and reservations, call 2734 9009. Internet bookings are available at www.urbtix.hk. For credit card telephone bookings, call 2111 5999. Visit www.hkifia.net for more information about the festival. Ends/Thursday, November 16, 2006
